# =============================================================================
# AmneziaWG Server List for Failover
# =============================================================================
#
# Format: NAME ENDPOINT_IP PORT PUBLIC_KEY
#
# - NAME: Friendly name for logging
# - ENDPOINT_IP: Server IP address (not hostname)
# - PORT: WireGuard port (usually 51820)
# - PUBLIC_KEY: THIS server's own public key (each server is unique — see the note below).
#   "-" reuses the key already in your base awg0.conf and is NOT a same-city shortcut.
#
# First server is PRIMARY - watchdog will failback to it when available
# Order matters - servers are tried in sequence during failover
#
# Get server list from your VPN provider:
# - Mullvad: https://api.mullvad.net/www/relays/all/ (fields: ipv4_addr_in, pubkey, active)
# - IVPN: https://www.ivpn.net/status
#
# =============================================================================
# IMPORTANT: EVERY SERVER HAS ITS OWN PUBLIC KEY
# =============================================================================
#
# With Mullvad (and most WireGuard providers) EACH server has a UNIQUE public key —
# including servers in the SAME city. us-lax-wg-001 and us-lax-wg-002 do NOT share a key.
# So put the real public key in column 4 for EVERY server you list.
#
# "-" means "reuse the key already in your base awg0.conf". That matches only the ONE server
# whose key is in awg0.conf — it is NOT a same-city shortcut. If you put "-" on any other
# server, the watchdog switches the endpoint to it but keeps the wrong key, and the handshake
# silently never completes: the tunnel goes dark with "0 B received" and no `latest handshake`.
# (This is a real failure mode — a stale "same cluster = same key" assumption is exactly how a
# failover list can look fine yet never actually fail over.) Don't use "-" for failover servers.
#
# Your CLIENT private key (in awg0.conf [Interface]) is account-wide and works on ALL of the
# provider's servers, so failover only needs each server's correct endpoint IP + its own key.
#
# For resilience, spread the pool across a few cities/providers so a single server, city, or
# provider outage still leaves a working path out. All-US servers keep a US exit (geo-unlock).
#
# =============================================================================

# Primary server (preferred; lowest latency to you). Each line: NAME  IP  PORT  ITS_OWN_PUBKEY
us-lax-wg-001   CHANGE_ME_IP   51820   CHANGE_ME_PUBKEY_1

# Failover servers — each needs ITS OWN public key (do NOT use "-"). Spread across cities.
us-lax-wg-002   CHANGE_ME_IP   51820   CHANGE_ME_PUBKEY_2
us-sjc-wg-001   CHANGE_ME_IP   51820   CHANGE_ME_PUBKEY_3
us-sea-wg-001   CHANGE_ME_IP   51820   CHANGE_ME_PUBKEY_4
us-den-wg-001   CHANGE_ME_IP   51820   CHANGE_ME_PUBKEY_5

# =============================================================================
# Example with explicit keys (every server distinct, even within a city):
# =============================================================================
#
# us-lax-wg-001   203.0.113.10    51820   LAX_001_PUBLIC_KEY
# us-lax-wg-002   203.0.113.11    51820   LAX_002_PUBLIC_KEY
# us-sjc-wg-001   198.51.100.10   51820   SJC_001_PUBLIC_KEY
# us-sea-wg-001   198.51.100.20   51820   SEA_001_PUBLIC_KEY
#
# IPs above are RFC 5737 documentation ranges - replace with real server IPs + keys.
# Save this file with UNIX (LF) line endings — a CRLF save can corrupt the last column (the key).
# =============================================================================
